As soon as data are received from 500 to 600 children, the study will continue with the Independencia Sport Centre (other than the Federal District) and in the Morelos Sports Centre (northly from the Federal Centre).
He explained that the aim of this research is to identify the components and importance of genetics in terms of the development of obesity, and to trace on Mexican children and young people risk factors and thus prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Day of diabetes celebrated on 14 November, he recalled that the aim was to collect data from three thousand children and young people between six and 14 years, with consent and under the supervision of parents, for the application of specific nutrition questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of inherited diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or kidney insufficiency.
He specified that each Saturday with all participants anthropometric measurements (weight, height, belt circumference), blood pressure is measured, glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulins are determined, and genes are tested (gens are identified that are involved in the formation of children’s obesity).
Cruz López said that this research reflects the concern of healthcare professionals over the alarming rise in child weight.
'A healthy survey carried out between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years only boys experienced an increase in obesity of 77% and 47% in girls. The dramatic increase also occurred in the case of overweight, he introduced an IMSS expert.
He said that one of the reasons for finding indicators is that the population of the country differs from other populations in their genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% Indian-American genetic equipment, 30% European and 5% African. This is reflected in genes that are responsible for the formation of diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity are commonly explained as inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and which is stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of the participants lies in the fact that they will receive a total assessment of the situation of children, thereby determining whether they have any known overweight or obesity.
He pointed out that even the presence of dark-coloured (acantosis) lines on the neck and foreclosure indicates that the individual would suffer from metabolic problems and pre-cushion conditions.
The information is confidential so far, the doctors transmit it in writing to their parents and explain to them all the measurements and changes in the lifestyle that must be made to avoid their children’s illness.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedating way of life that represents a lack of daily physical activity, a daily sitting before television and the use of means of transport rather than a short distance walk.
The overweight also causes large calorie intakes, this is greater consumption of chilled drinks, hydrohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetic burden that is covered by this research.
