Nord Stream, a new Russian gas port to Europe
Nord Stream remote gas pipeline connecting directly Eastern Europe to Russia and led down the Baltic Sea began to work.
They must supply gas equal to equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas industry, wanted to celebrate this event properly.
More than 500 guests, including 4 Heads of State and Government, attended the inauguration of Nord Stream last Tuesday, a new pipeline that will join Russia and Germany directly under the sea.
The symbolic German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedív, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch colleague Mark Rutte turned together in control around the valve of the Russian gas input into the Western European network.
This new gas pipeline starts to flow each year to Western Europe 27.5 billion additional cubic metres of Russian gas by the first pipeline of 1 224 km connecting the Petrohrad region to the Mecklembursko-Poransian Land.
The second pipe, which must be completed at the end of 2012, will supply a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, a quantity equal to the whole French consumption.
And it is recalled that there is a possibility to build a third pipeline on the same route.
For Gazprom, it is early to complete this huge structure of victory.
The project strongly protested Poland and the Baltic countries against the project.
Nord Stream will in fact allow the gas to be supplied directly to Germany without being led by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
At the same time, these two countries are losing some power: the possibility of pressure on Russia by threats of closing it into the Western European markets becomes more difficult for them.
It was not most pronounced by Warsaw when she did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to the "German-Soviet Pact", with reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin in the occupation of Poland in 1939.
It means saying it's a subject politically sensitive.
Western Europe has gained greater security of its purchases in this Russian project.
But it is at the cost of weakening Europe of energy, because the project has created cracks between Eastern Europeans and the West.
Russia managed barely five years ago to promote its vision of direct alliance between Russia and rich Western states with high gas consumption, whose bearings are approaching their end.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that organicises us", confirmed François Fillon during the opening ceremony of this gas pipeline and demonstrated at what point there are large gas contracts of things both political and economic.
This explains all the wide smiles of the Gazprom leaders present in large numbers in Lubmin, the incoming gas place.
The construction of this pipeline is also a major technical act.
The underwater pipe is made of steel fitted with a concrete envelope to protect from seagoing vessels.
It lies at the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
During its construction, minefields from World War II had to be avoided.
"Because of their safety, almost a hundred had to be removed or destroyed," says Jens Müller, spokesperson to Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to increase measures for the protection of fauna and flora.
The pipeline itself is a long metal hose weighing 242 Eiffel, which is not interrupted anywhere by valves or maintenance stations throughout its length.
One control platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project leader rejected it when the Swedish people were few eager to see the Russian state company, as permanently settled near their coast.
"In case of failure, we stop the gas passage in less than 1 minute", explains Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas contained in the pipeline will escape into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builders, but the welds were designed to make the leak once in 100,000 years.
Control of the outside gas pipeline is carried out by an underwater robot drawn by a ship, while the inside of the pipeline is controlled by a device that circulation inside.
Thisnut shape device with a diameter of 1 metre is introduced into the inside of the pipe and is compressed by gas.
Within the target, 3 m/s will provide accurate information on possible deformations of metal parts throughout the three days of the journey.
The remote gas pipeline has been designed to work for 50 years without the need for more self-repair.
Gas circulation is easily secured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar in the target.
To realize this project, five companies joined forces.
The head of the position remains Gazprom, which holds a share of 51%.
It was joined by the German company E.ON and BASF (5.5% each), as well as the Dutch company Gasunie and the French GDF Suez group (9% each).
These five companies created a joint venture called Nord Stream, which was entrusted with the construction and operation of the pipeline.
The company has its registered office in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely beneficial.
Gasprom subsequently rented it for five years with a contract that can be renewed all its capacity for gas transport.
"Gazprom will have a profit from total capacity, whatever the amount of gas actually transported", explains Jens Müller.
The financing of the pipeline was provided with 30% of its shareholders and 70% of bank loans.
Total labour costs should be € 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For the GDF Suez Group, investment costs reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that their costs will return, because the risk is taken by Gazprom only.
Gas pipeline is coming from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on the sandy coast with pine forests.
Ventils of a height of 4,5 metres form an exit gas gate.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before being transported to the German pipelines.
From Tuesday, this terminal has received one million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour.
When capacity is reached, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012 6 million.
